### Single-Line Comment
A single-line comment is used to add brief explanations or notes for a specific line of code.
It is ignored during program execution.
Example :
This is a single-line comment
age = 23  # Stores the user's age

### Multi-Line Comment
A multi-line comment is used to describe logic, functions, or blocks of code in detail.
It is useful for documentation or longer explanations.
Example:
"""
This is a multi-line comment.
It can span multiple lines.
Used for detailed explanations or documentation.
"""
name = "Kiruba"

### Variables
Variables are used to store values in memory.
Example:
Age = 23
Name = "Kiruba"

### Multiple Assignments
Multiple assignment allows assigning values to multiple variables in a single line.
Example:
a, b, c = 10, 20, 30
x = y = z = 5

### Data Types
Data types define the type of value a variable can store.
Python is a dynamically typed language, meaning the data type is determined automatically at runtime.
=> Numeric Types
Used to store numerical values.
Types:
## int – Integer numbers
Example :
a = 10     
## float – Decimal numbers
Example :
b = 10.5       
## complex – Complex numbers
Example : 
c = 2 + 3j 

=>String (str)
Used to store textual data enclosed in quotes.
Example:
name = "Kiruba"
message = 'Hello World'

=>Boolean (bool)
Represents logical values.
## Values:
True
False
Example:
is_active = True
is_logged_in = False

=>Sequence Types
Used to store ordered collections of items.
## List (list) – Mutable collection
Example : 
numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4]
## Tuple (tuple) – Immutable collection
Example : 
coordinates = (10, 20)
## Range (range) – Sequence of numbers
Example : 
values = range(5)

=> Set Type
Unordered collection of unique elements.
unique_numbers = {1, 2, 3, 3}

=> Mapping Type
Stores data as key–value pairs.
## Dictionary (dict)
EXample : 
student = {
    "name": "Kiruba",
    "age": 23
}

=> None Type
Represents absence of a value.
Example :
data = None
